e language and organization of the political coalitions on either side of the debate. Krinsky’s broadly interdisciplinary analysis draws from interviews, official documents, and media reports to pursue new directions in the study of the cultural and cognitive aspects of political activism. Free Labor will instigate a lively dialogue among students of culture, labor and social movements, welfare policy, and urban political economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEmployee rightsxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aEmployee rightszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aWelfare recipientsxEmploymentxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aWelfare recipientsxEmploymentzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aWelfare rights movementxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aWelfare rights movementzNew York (State)zNew York. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aworker, workforce, laborer, job, career, professional, language, linguistics, neoliberal, neoliberalism, politics, political, philosophy, philosophical, history, historical, academic, scholarly, research, new york city, rudolph giuliani, work experience, program, welfare, urban, policies, employee, union, unionized, authority, power.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226453675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226453675/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles